Brake fluid has the ability to absorb moisture in the air, lowering its boiling point and adversely changing its operating characteristics. When its boiling point drops (greater than 230 °C for a new fluid), high temperatures are generated during prolonged braking and the fluid, which has even the slightest water content, turns to steam. The resulting vapour is compressible and thus reduces the effects of the brake fluid.     Use: Remove the wheel where you plan to vent.
